raw_text:
US adds more jobs than expected
 
 The US economy added 337,000 jobs in October - a seven-month high and far more than Wall Street expectations.
 
 In a welcome economic boost for newly re-elected President George W Bush, the Labor Department figures come after a slow summer of weak jobs gains. Jobs were created in every sector of the US economy except manufacturing. While the separate unemployment rate went up to 5.5% from 5.4% in September, this was because more people were now actively seeking work.
 
 The 337,000 new jobs added to US payrolls in October was twice the 169,000 figure that Wall Street economists had forecast. In addition, the Labor Department revised up the number of jobs created in the two previous months - to 139,000 in September instead of 96,000, and to 198,000 in August instead of 128,000. The better than expected jobs data had an immediate upward effect on stocks in New York, with the main Dow Jones index gaining 45.4 points to 10,360 by late morning trading. "It looks like the job situation is improving and that this will support consumer spending going into the holidays, and offset some of the drag caused by high oil prices this year," said economist Gary Thayer of AG Edwards & Sons.
 
 Other analysts said the upbeat jobs data made it more likely that the US Federal Reserve would increase interest rates by a quarter of a percentage point to 2% when it meets next week. "It should empower the Fed to clearly do something," said Robert MacIntosh, chief economist with Eaton Vance Management in Boston. Kathleen Utgoff, commissioner of the Bureau of Labor, said many of the 71,000 new construction jobs added in October were involved in rebuilding and clean-up work in Florida, and neighbouring Deep South states, following four hurricanes in August and September. The dollar rose temporarily on the job creation news before falling back to a new record low against the euro, as investors returned their attention to other economic factors, such as the US's record trade deficit. There is also speculation that President Bush will deliberately try to keep the dollar low in order to assist a growth in exports.

tinydolphin:1.1b:
The United States government added more jobs than expected in October, according to data from the Labor Department. The revised estimate shows job creation increased by 337,000 to a seasonally adjusted total of 3,510,000. The previous estimate, released on September 24, forecasted fewer than 1,000,000 new jobs.

The October increase in job growth is significant for the US economy, which has been slow to recover from a slow summer of weak employment gains. Preliminary data from the Bureau of Labor showed that construction sector jobs increased by over 71,000, marking a seven-month high and well above Wall Street expectations. The increase in September was driven by hurricane-related cleanup work in Florida.

The Labor Department's data also reveals that the unemployment rate increased to 5.5% from 5.4% in September, but this was primarily due to an increase in the number of people actively seeking work. The separate unemployment rate rose to 5.7%, indicating a slight uptick in jobless rates across various sectors of the economy.

The October jobs report comes as the US stock market experienced a significant upward spike following the release of the revised data, with the Dow Jones index gaining 45.4 points to 10,360 by late morning trading in New York. This improvement in job creation could have an immediate positive impact on consumer spending, as higher employment levels can lead to increased demand for goods and services.

Analysts are projecting that the US Federal Reserve will increase interest rates by a quarter of a percentage point at its next meeting, which is expected to be held next week in Washington D.C. If this decision is made, it could bolster the US economy by stimulating borrowing and investment. However, this could also lead to further price inflation for consumers, who will face higher costs for goods and services.

In summary, the October jobs report by the Labor Department reveals that the US economy added 3,510,000 new jobs in October, exceeding Wall Street expectations and providing a welcome boost to both newly re-elected President George W. Bush and American workers. The revised job creation data supports the idea that the US economy is improving and could support consumer spending during the holiday season. However, this could also lead to further price inflation for consumers, putting pressure on future interest rates decisions by the Federal Reserve.
